reviewText:
Hello guys!

The Vanishing of Ethan Carter is a great story/game that, in my opinion, should be tried out by every person who loves mysticsm and craves for a good written tale.

At first, the game will impress you with stunning landscape views and beautiful graphics (although at some places it wasn't polished to the limits). It feels real. I mean really real, although it sounds kind of ridiculous. Well, at least when you do not look really closely. Wind is slowly swinging grass, tress, bushes and etc. Combining this with abandoned railroad and houses and, of course, mountain range environment the game creates feelings of lonelyness and melancholy. But after a few tens of minutes player will realise that something really weird is happening around there. Or maybe was happening...

After this, the game will make you think. Not too hard, not too much. but still think... How to solve, where's the catch. Because the more you solve, the more story you'll uncover. And thus the game gets as interesting, as it is beautiful. And even if you won't be able to solve everything and leave some mysteries behind, you will still get to the very end of the game to see, to know what really happened there...

And now i'll put aside my emotions and feelings and try to point out some pros and cons of this game.

Pros:
-interesting story with a few or even none flaws in it;
-breathtaking and detailed environment;
-kind of empty but still alive world;
-really good soundtrack;
-simple game mechanics;
-even more interesting when played with someone.

Objective cons:
-seems to be overpriced for its length;
-later on the puzzles give you the feeling that they are a bit unfinished (at least some of them);
-is really violent (I wouldn't recommend this for underaged or really sensitive people).

Subjective cons:
-puzzles were too easy for me with most of them taking like 5-7 minutes to solve them;
-in my opinion, it would be great if the puzzles had a little different solution mechanics and would make you to think more;
-i'm not sure if this was my machine but I had some minor lags and one bug that needed a game restart to be solved.

For the record, I played this with my girlfriend who isn't a fan of computer games. But she enjoyed this game a lot, loved the story, loved the time we spent for it.

So... This game is really worth to buy and play, even if it's short and overpriced. Want to buy a book with a good plot and sophisticated point of view towards the world? Do it... But consider this game as well, because it's almost as good as any of Stephen Kings' horror stories.

Short update: in my review the time spent for this game is not shown correctly - with long strolls and taking time to enjoy the views this game took me about 6 hours to complete it with doing all the achievements.

